+## Humanize All Non-Code Prose
+
+Apply the `humanizer` skill to ALL non-code text output throughout the entire brainstorming workflow. This includes:
+
+- **Design presentations** (approach proposals, design section walkthroughs)
+- **Spec documents** (the written design doc saved to disk)
+- **Plan prose** (goal descriptions, architecture summaries, task descriptions in plans)
+- **Questions and explanations** (clarifying questions, approach reasoning)
+
+**Does NOT apply to:** code blocks, file paths, commands, configuration snippets, or structured data (tables, checklists).
+
+**How to apply:** Before presenting any non-code prose to the user or writing it to a file, mentally run it through the humanizer patterns. Strip AI-isms inline as you write - don't produce slop then clean it up. Specifically watch for:
+- Significance inflation ("pivotal", "crucial", "vital role", "testament")
+- Promotional language ("vibrant", "groundbreaking", "seamless")
+- Copula avoidance ("serves as", "stands as" instead of "is")
+- Superficial -ing phrases ("highlighting", "underscoring", "fostering")
+- Rule-of-three lists, negative parallelisms ("not just X, but Y")
+- Filler ("in order to", "it is important to note")
+- Sycophantic openers ("Great question!", "Absolutely!")
+- Generic positive conclusions ("the future looks bright")
+- Em dash overuse, excessive boldface, emoji decoration
+- Inline-header vertical lists (prefer flowing prose)
+
+Write like a person talking to another person. Vary sentence rhythm. Have opinions. Be specific.
+
+## Document Pros and Cons for Every Decision
+
+Every design decision, architecture choice, library selection, or approach recommendation must include explicit pros and cons. This applies throughout the entire workflow:
+
+**During brainstorming:**
+- Each of the 2-3 proposed approaches needs a pros/cons list
+- When recommending one approach, explain which cons you're accepting and why
+
+**In spec documents:**
+- Architecture decisions get a "Pros / Cons / Why we chose this" block
+- Library or tool selections get the same treatment
+- If a decision has no meaningful cons, you probably haven't thought hard enough about it
+
+**In implementation plans:**
+- Task-level design choices (data structure selection, API shape, error handling strategy) include brief pros/cons
+- Keep it proportional: a minor choice gets a one-liner each, a major choice gets a full list
+
+**Format:** Keep it simple. No elaborate tables needed. Just:
+- Pros: what you gain
+- Cons: what you give up or risk
+- (Optional) Why: the tiebreaker reasoning if not obvious
+
+**Auto-select obvious winners:** If one option has only pros and no cons compared to the alternatives (or its cons are strictly a subset of every other option's cons), auto-select it. Still show all options with their pros/cons so the reasoning is visible, but announce: "Auto-selected option N — it has no downsides compared to the alternatives. Let me know if you'd prefer a different choice." If the user doesn't object, proceed with it.
+
+**The point is not ceremony.** It's making trade-offs visible so the user (and future readers of the spec/plan) can see what was considered and why.
+
