+## Post-Implementation Polish (always, via subagent named in the plan)
+
+After the last per-task review passes, **always** run the polish pipeline. Do NOT skip it, do NOT run it inline, and do NOT ask the user.
+
+Read the `Polish: post-implementation-polish → <agent type>` line from the plan's `## Agent Assignments` section. Dispatch the polish subagent using **that** agent type — do not re-pick. If the line is missing, fall back to `general-purpose` and note the gap so writing-plans can fix it next time.
+
+The polish subagent owns all six phases (three review rounds, idiomatic pass, /cleanup, strip + humanize comments). Only after it reports DONE do you transition to `finishing-a-development-branch`.
+
+```
+Task tool (<agent type from plan's Polish line>):
+  description: "Run post-implementation polish on the full diff"
+  prompt: |
+    You own the post-implementation-polish skill end-to-end for this branch.
+
+    Plan: <path to plan file>
+    Spec: <path to spec file>
+    Base SHA: <git merge-base HEAD main>
+    Head SHA: <git rev-parse HEAD>
+
+    Read the post-implementation-polish skill and execute ALL six phases in order:
+      1. Code review round 1 (+ fixes, commit)
+      2. Code review round 2 (+ fixes, commit) — skip if round 1 was clean
+      3. Code review round 3 (+ fixes, commit) — skip if round 2 was clean
+      4. Idiomatic code pass
+      5. /cleanup (simplify) with fixes
+      6. Strip AI comments, then humanize remaining comments
+
+    Do not run any phase in parallel — each builds on the previous.
+    Do not modify code logic in phase 6.
+    Commit between phases.
+
+    Report back: phases run, phases skipped (with reason), commits made, any unresolved findings.
+```
+
+If polish itself surfaces unresolved Critical/Important findings, treat them as a regression: dispatch a fix subagent, then re-run the affected polish phase. Loop until clean (max 10 iterations across the whole polish stage), then surface to the user.
+
