+## Batching: Parallel Where Independent, Sequential Where Dependent
+
+Read the plan's `## Task Dependency Graph` section to compute batches:
+
+- A **batch** is a set of tasks whose `depends on` lists are all satisfied (every predecessor's review passed).
+- The first batch is every task with `depends on: none`. Dispatch ALL of them in parallel — one Task tool call per task in the same response. Use the agent types from `## Agent Assignments`.
+- After every task in the current batch passes its per-task two-stage review (spec compliance + code quality), compute the next batch (every pending task whose predecessors are now complete) and dispatch that batch in parallel.
+- Continue until all tasks are done. A plan with no parallelism is just a chain of single-task batches.
+
+**Why this matters:** parallel dispatch of independent tasks is the whole point of subagents. Don't run independent tasks one-at-a-time — that wastes the orchestration model. But never speculatively parallelise tasks that share files or consume each other's output; that causes merge conflicts and broken interfaces. Default to sequential when independence is not obvious from the dependency graph.
+
+**Single-task plans:** trivially one batch with one dispatch. No parallelism overhead, but still via subagent — never inline.
+
+**If the plan lacks `## Task Dependency Graph`:** default every task to "depends on prior task" (full sequential chain) and note the gap so writing-plans can add the section next time. Better safe-sequential than unsafe-parallel.
